Conflicts can occur when two parties do not want to understand each other,after a while the parties may become so entrenched that they cannot find a solution to their problem themselves. 
In 2009 the late Mr. Ma Mun, husband and father, passed away, leaving behind his wife VenEng, 63 years old,and stepdaughter Mamun Kimsour, 33 years old, both residents of Preak village, PreakKouy Commune, S’ang District, Kandal Province, Mamun Kimsour works as a garment factory worker at a Korean garment factory.
On receiving the request to mediate the conflict, ADHOC conducted research on the background of the case and found the following:
The conflict arose in November 2012 when Ms. Kimsour learned that her stepmother, Ms. Ven Eng, registered the house and farmland of the late Mr. Ma Mun to her own name, excluding Ms. Kimsour.
Ms. Kimsour disagreed with this act of her stepmother as it excluded her from what she felt was her rightful inheritance, and submitted a complaint to the local authorities,however, by December the local authorities had failed to act in regard to the complaint filed by Ms. Kimsour. Thus, on the 15th of December Ms.Kimsour submitted a complaint to Kandal court to have her inheritance rights sustained.
However, Ms. Kimsour lost the case at the Kandal court, she filed her complaint at Appeal court and contacted ADHOC with the request to  provide her with legal representation,During the preparatory sessions, Ms. Kimsour explained that it was her objective to acquire 20,000.00USD from her share of the value of the house and was entitled to 26m x 225m of the family farmland. 
During meetings with Ms.Ven Eng the ADHOC mediator explained that going through the court case could take a long time and would cost addition stress and money, this was confirmed by Ms. Ven Eng’sson, who explained that “his mother paid around 10,000.00USD for this case”.